import scipy.stats
from scipy.stats import chi2

contingency_table=pd.crosstab(data1["outcome"],data1["poutcome_of_campaign"])
print('contingency_table :-\n',contingency_table)

contingency_table :-
 poutcome_of_campaign     0    1   2      3
outcome                                   
0                     1384  510  66  27849
1                       55   28  15   1742
In [132]:
#Observed Values
Observed_Values = contingency_table.values 
print("Observed Values :-\n",Observed_Values)

Observed Values :-
 [[ 1384   510    66 27849]
 [   55    28    15  1742]]
In [133]:
#Expected Values
import scipy.stats
b=scipy.stats.chi2_contingency(contingency_table)
Expected_Values = b[3]
print("Expected Values :-\n",Expected_Values)

Expected Values :-
 [[1.35533985e+03 5.06721919e+02 7.62908465e+01 2.78706474e+04]
 [8.36601472e+01 3.12780815e+01 4.70915353e+00 1.72035262e+03]]
In [134]:
#DEGREES OF FREEDOM
df=b[2]
print("Degree of Freedom:-",df)

Degree of Freedom:- 3
In [135]:
alpha=0.05
In [136]:
chi_square=sum([(o-e)**2./e for o,e in zip(Observed_Values,Expected_Values)])
chi_square_statistic=chi_square[0]+chi_square[1]
print("chi-square statistic:-",chi_square_statistic)

chi-square statistic:- 10.78915745503087
In [137]:
#p-value
p_value=1-chi2.cdf(x=chi_square_statistic,df=df)
print('p-value:',p_value)

p-value: 0.012922363461103092

So, We can tell that Previous Outcome also has Significant Dependence with the outcome
